data.enText: a small piece of metal or plastic, with a design or words on it, that a person wears to show that they belong to an organization, support sth, have achieved sth, have a particular rank, etc.

data.chText: 她戴着一枚徽章，上面写着“投科茨一票”。
data.enText: She wore a badge saying ‘Vote for Coates’.

data.chText: 所有员工均须佩戴名牌。
data.enText: All employees have to wear name badges.
a piece of material that you sew onto clothes as part of a uniform
a small piece of metal that you carry or wear to prove who you are, used, for example, by police officers

data.chText: 他拿出工作证，说他是警察。
data.enText: He pulled out a badge and said he was a cop.
something that shows that a particular quality is present

data.chText: 他的枪对他而言是权力的标志。
data.enText: His gun was a badge of power for him.

synonyms.bx: 由金属或其他材料制成，表明身份、职衔、所支持的团体等。
用布制成，缝在军人或警察制服的袖子上，表明佩戴者的军衔或警衔。
常印于银器、盘碟或信笺上，象征某一家族、机构等的历史悠久。

ex.enText: The thistle is the emblem of Scotland.

synonyms.bx: 通常用于代表国家、团体等。

ex.chText: 她佩戴了一枚钻石胸针。

synonyms.bx: 指佩戴在胸前作为饰件的胸针，或带有别针的徽章，作后者解时尤用于美国英语。

d.text: 饰针，胸针；（背面有别针的）徽章

tips.tip: 英国英语中用 brooch 表示“胸针”。

tr: any feature that is regarded as a sign of status (a particular power or quality or rank)
example: wearing a tie was regarded as a badge of respectability

tr: an emblem (a small piece of plastic or cloth or metal) that signifies your status (rank or membership or affiliation etc.)
example: they checked everyone's badge before letting them in
The workers here must be badged

value.def: A badge is a piece of metal or cloth which you wear to show that you belong to an organization or support a cause. American English usually uses button to refer to a small round metal badge.
value.tran: 徽章，证章（美国英语通常用button指金属小圆徽章）

value.def: Any feature which is regarded as a sign of a particular quality can be referred to as a badge .

example.ex: Being a Communist was a badge of honour for thousands of trade union activists.
example.tran: 对数千工会积极分子来说，成为共产党员是荣誉的象征。
